<TITLE> Japan salvages tax measures from political deadlock </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TOKYO, March 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Japan's ruling and opposition parties agreed on Friday to extend special tax measures such as withholding tax exemptions on cross-border financing, to limit the fallout from a broader policy deadlock. In a paralysis born of a divided parliament and feuding over a controversial gasoline tax, Japan had risked being unable to extend a slew of special tax measures due to expire this month. But parties, including the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and the main opposition Democratic Party, agreed to extend tax measures other than those related to funding roads till the end of May, Kyodo news agency reported. The Democrats, which with smaller allies control parliament's upper house and can delay laws, have demanded the government abolish a "provisional" gasoline tax whose revenues are devoted to road construction. Prime Minister Yasuo Fukuda has refused to scrap the tax from April, saying that doing so now would leave a huge revenue gap in national and local budgets. Analysts said the failure to extend all of the special tax measures was expected to hurt Japan's global status even if it meant no major impact on money flows in the financial market. Tax measures extended to May include an exemption on a withholding tax in Japan's offshore market and a reduced tax related to land transactions. The political stalemate has also left the central bank without a permanent governor for the first time in more than 80 years after the upper house rejected two government nominees for the post. The deadlock has sparked speculation that Fukuda's ruling party might try to replace him ahead of a general election that could come this ye
